To directly answer whether a specific piece of code pushes every element in an array back one position depends on the actual code snippet in question, which wasn't provided in your query. However, I can explain the general concept of how elements in an array can be moved (or "pushed") back by one position, and provide a simple example.

### Concept

"Pushing back" elements in an array context usually means moving elements to make space for a new element at the beginning of the array or at a specific position. This process involves iterating through the array from the end or the insertion point, shifting each element one position to the right (towards the end of the array). This must be done in reverse order (starting from the end) to prevent overwriting elements.

### Example

Here's an example in C++ that demonstrates pushing every element in an array back by one position to insert a new value at the beginning of the array:

```cpp
#include <iostream>

void pushBackAndInsert(int arr[], int& size, int newValue, int capacity) {
    // Check if there's space to add an element.
    if (size >= capacity) {
        std::cout << "Array is at full capacity. Cannot insert new element." << std::endl;
        return;
    }

    // Move elements back starting from the end.
    for (int i = size; i > 0; --i) {
        arr[i] = arr[i - 1];
    }

    // Insert the new value at the beginning.
    arr[0] = newValue;
    // Increment the size to reflect the added element.
    ++size;
}

int main() {
    // Example usage.
    const int capacity = 10; // Maximum capacity of the array.
    int arr[capacity] = {2, 3, 4, 5}; // Initial array, not at full capacity.
    int size = 4; // Current size of the array.

    // Element to insert.
    int newValue = 1;

    // Function call to push back elements and insert a new value.
    pushBackAndInsert(arr, size, newValue, capacity);

    // Output the modified array.
    for (int i = 0; i < size; ++i) {
        std::cout << arr[i] << " ";
    }
    std::cout << std::endl;

    return 0;
